      "text": "Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. 317.249-5400 www.misoenergy.org\n\n720 City Center Drive Carmel, Indiana 46032\n\n2985 Ames Crossing Road Eagan, Minnesota 55121\n\n1700 Centerview Drive Little Rock, AR 72211\n\nSarah Nieman \nCorporate Counsel \nDirect Dial: 317-502-0041 \nEmail: sanieman@misoenergy.org \n\nDecember 5, 2025\n\nVIA ELECTRONIC FILING\n\nThe Honorable Debbie-Anne A. Reese \nSecretary \nFederal Energy Regulatory Commission \n888 First Street, NE \nWashington, DC 20426 \n\nRe: Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. Revisions to the Open Access Transmission, Energy and Operating Reserve Markets Tariff Attachment X Improvements and Clarifications Filing Docket No. ER26-____-000\n\nDear Secretary Reese:\n\nThe Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) submits this filing 1 to revise its Open Access Transmission, Energy and Operating Reserve Markets Tariff (“Tariff”) 2 to amend its Attachment X, Generator Interconnection Procedures (“GIP”) and Attachment X, Appendix 6, Generator Interconnection Agreement (“GIA”). 3 This proposal: (1) implements a lower insurance requirement for smaller generators (the “Insurance Requirements Proposal”); (2) clarifies when a valid interconnection request is deemed complete by the Transmission Provider (the “Queue Priority Proposal”); (3) clarifies that a Generating Facility may only be under the control of one Transmission Provider even if it is connected to a neighboring Transmission Provider (the “One Transmission Provider Proposal”); and (4) corrects miscellaneous ministerial errors in both the GIA and the JTIQ Commitment Agreement that have come to MISO’s attention (the “Clerical Errors Correction Proposal”).\n\n1 MISO makes this filing pursuant to Section 205 of the Federal Power Act (“FPA”), 16 U.S.C. § 824d, and Part 35 of the regulations of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC” or “Commission”), 18 C.F.R. § 35.1, et seq.\n\n2 All capitalized terms not otherwise defined herein shall have the meaning as set forth in the Tariff or the proposed revisions, as applicable.\n\n3 The GIP and GIA are set forth in Attachment X of the Tariff.\n\nThis filing consists of four (4) separate and severable proposals to make certain improvements to the GIP and other parts of the Tariff. See NRG Power Mktg., LLC v. FERC, 862 F.3d 108, 115 (D.C. Cir. 2017). 4 MISO includes them together for administrative efficiency and the avoidance of multiple unnecessary Tariff versions. However, each is independently warranted and does not reflect tradeoffs or compromises with other proposals. MISO requests an effective date of February 4, 2026, which is 61 days after the date of this filing.\n\nI. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY\n\nMISO is submitting this filing to make several clarifications to its Tariff, only one of which is a new addition of Tariff language. First, MISO is changing the insurance requirements for small generators eligible under the FERC Fast Track Process to lower the required carrying amount. Second, MISO is adding language to its Tariff to clarify and make explicit within MISO’s GIP and GIA that Generating Facilities may only be until the control of one Transmission Provider at a time, which reflects MISO’s long-held practice in alignment with NERC’s Rules of Procedure. Third, MISO is cleaning up language related to Interconnection Requests that should have been removed following the addition of the DPP Queue cap and the ERAS cap processes to clarify when an Interconnection Request is assigned queue priority and the effect of deficiencies. Finally, MISO proposes to correct several clerical errors in the JTIQ Commitment Agreement (Attachment X, Appendix 18 to the GIP) and a reference error to this agreement in the GIA appendices. For efficiency, MISO is proposing to make all of these changes in one Tariff update filing.\n\nII. BACKGROUND OF MISO’S PROPOSALS\n\nA. Insurance Requirements\n\nEarlier this year in MISO’s Stakeholder Process, a stakeholder proposed updating MISO’s insurance requirements for small generators (i.e. ≤ 5 MW) under MISO’s pro forma GIA to align with the reduced insurance requirements applicable to such generators under the Commissions pro forma Small Generator Interconnection Agreement. 5 MISO does not utilize a separate agreement\n\n4 This is a “non-integrated” filing for purposes of NRG Power Mktg., LLC v. FERC, 862 F.3d 108, 115 (D.C. Cir. 2017) (“NRG”). The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit explained in NRG that under FPA section 205 the FERC may accept or reject a rate proposal by a public utility, or require some minor modifications if the public utility consents to those modifications, but cannot “impose a new rate of its own making” regardless of the public utility consent. Id. at 114-15. As the Court explained, “although ‘minor deviations’ from a proposal are permissible, ‘the imposition by the Commission of only half of a proposed rate’ is not permissible.” Id. at 115. These strictures do not apply, however, when a public utility includes several independent (i.e., “non-integrated”) rate proposals in one filing, such as the case here. Accordingly, MISO requests that the Commission review each of the proposals included in this filing, i.e., the Insurance Requirements Proposal, the Queue Priority Proposal, the One Transmission Provider Proposal, and the Clerical Errors Correction Proposal independently.\n\n5 See GIA Small Generator Insurance Requirements 5 MW and Under (PAC-2025-1), proposed by Dan Juhl, Hybrid Renewables, 2025 Interconnection Process Working Group, (Mar. 4, 2025), available at: https://cdn.misoenergy.org/20250304%20IPWG%20Item%2007%20GIA%20Small%20Generator%20Insuranc e%20Requirements%205%20MW%20and%20Under%20(PAC-2025-1)_Hybrid%20Renewables681918.pdf.\n\nfor small generators, although such generators are processed through an expedited fast track procedure under Section 14 of MISO’s GIP. 6\n\nThe stakeholder requested this change, claiming the existing requirement in MISO’s pro forma GIA for large generators “can make small generator development unnecessarily uneconomic and infeasible.” 7 Article 18.4.4 of MISO’s pro forma GIA currently requires Interconnection Customers to carry excess public liability insurance with a minimum of $20 million per occurrence and $20 million aggregate regardless of the size of the Generating Facility. MISO continues to believe that its current unified GIA construct is appropriate for the MISO region. However, after extensive engagement with stakeholders and careful consideration, MISO does agree that it can accommodate stakeholder desires for a reduced insurance requirement for small generators within its GIA without creating inefficiencies or unreasonable risks to the Transmission System.\n\nOver the past year, MISO worked with stakeholders to develop new language for smaller generator interconnection requests and is now proposing to change its pro forma GIA to reduce the insurance requirements in its GIA from $20 million to $5 million for ≤ 5 MW generators. Specifically, MISO proposes to add language to GIA Article 18.4.4 to set a new minimum insurance requirement of a combined single limit of $5 million per occurrence and $5 million in aggregate for ≤ 5 MW generators.\n\nThis proposal is just, reasonable, and warranted for several reasons. First, it aligns MISO’s insurance requirements for small generators with those adopted by the Commission under the pro forma SGIA. Second, it responds to stakeholder desires to ease a cost barrier on small generators as the lower limit policies can be obtained for lower premiums. Third, MISO has determined that based on accumulated experience with small generating facilities, adopting this lower insurance requirement will still provide sufficient protection for the Transmission System, especially given the lower voltages at which such small generating facilities tend to interconnect. Finally, MISO notes that generating facilities of ≤ 5 MW remain rare in the MISO region. Incorporating this co",
